ass sizes and the sense of community of the school, but not necessarily agree with all the Catholic teachings.  I also recognize the public school's efforts, diversity, and services they offer to our children that catholic schools may not offer especially to those with special needs...We do need some reformation, which should be led by the frontline in education, i.e. Teachers, Students, &amp; Parents...not privatized companies... Finland seems to have a great model for public education, leaving the schools to decide what is best for the children rather than standardized testing and state legislature, teaching the whole child philosophy...here is the article if interested...  Schools we can envy by Diane Ravitch Glad there is a discussion about private and public education! "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1088" language="en" documentId="2661" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="MP Special Education Teacher" date="Aug 29, 2013 8:31PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="2661" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1088"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>